      "heading_text": "Partial updates with PATCH",
      "anchor_id": "partial-updates-with-patch",
      "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#partial-updates-with-patch",
      "section_text": "You can also use the HTTP PATCH operation to partially update data.\n\nThis means that you can send only the data that you want to update, leaving the rest intact.",
      "section_inline_code": [
        "PATCH"
      ],
      "section_links": [
        {
          "text": "HTTP",
          "url": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Methods/PATCH",
          "section_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0004",
          "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#partial-updates-with-patch"
        }
      ],
      "code_refs": [],
      "code_blocks": []
    },
    "tutorial/body-updates::section-0005": {
      "node_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0005",
      "parent_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0004",
      "level": 3,
      "node_kind": "heading",
      "heading_text": "Using Pydantic's exclude_unset parameter",
      "anchor_id": "using-pydantics-exclude-unset-parameter",
      "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#using-pydantics-exclude-unset-parameter",
      "section_text": "If you want to receive partial updates, it's very useful to use the parameter exclude_unset in Pydantic's model's .model_dump() .\n\nLike item.model_dump(exclude_unset=True) .\n\nThat would generate a dict with only the data that was set when creating the item model, excluding default values.\n\nThen you can use this to generate a dict with only the data that was set (sent in the request), omitting default values:",
      "section_inline_code": [
        "exclude_unset",
        ".model_dump()",
        "item.model_dump(exclude_unset=True)",
        "dict",
        "item"
      ],
      "section_links": [],
      "code_refs": [
        {
          "type": "code_ref",
          "path": "../../docs_src/body_updates/tutorial002_py310.py",
          "highlight_lines": [
            32
          ],
          "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/body_updates/tutorial002_py310.py hl[32] *}",
          "section_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0005",
          "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#using-pydantics-exclude-unset-parameter"
        }
      ],
      "code_blocks": []
    },
    "tutorial/body-updates::section-0006": {
      "node_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0006",
      "parent_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0004",
      "level": 3,
      "node_kind": "heading",
      "heading_text": "Using Pydantic's update parameter",
      "anchor_id": "using-pydantics-update-parameter",
      "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#using-pydantics-update-parameter",
      "section_text": "Now, you can create a copy of the existing model using .model_copy() , and pass the update parameter with a dict containing the data to update.\n\nLike stored_item_model.model_copy(update=update_data) :",
      "section_inline_code": [
        "update",
        ".model_copy()",
        "dict",
        "stored_item_model.model_copy(update=update_data)"
      ],
      "section_links": [],
      "code_refs": [
        {
          "type": "code_ref",
          "path": "../../docs_src/body_updates/tutorial002_py310.py",
          "highlight_lines": [
            33
          ],
          "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/body_updates/tutorial002_py310.py hl[33] *}",
          "section_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0006",
          "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#using-pydantics-update-parameter"
        }
      ],
      "code_blocks": []
    },
    "tutorial/body-updates::section-0007": {
      "node_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0007",
      "parent_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0004",
      "level": 3,
      "node_kind": "heading",
      "heading_text": "Partial updates recap",
      "anchor_id": "partial-updates-recap",
      "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#partial-updates-recap",
      "section_text": "In summary, to apply partial updates you would:\n\n- (Optionally) use PATCH instead of PUT .\n\n- Retrieve the stored data.\n\n- Put that data in a Pydantic model.\n\n- This way you can update only the values actually set by the user, instead of overriding values already stored with default values in your model.\n\n- This is comparable to using the model's .model_dump() method again, but it makes sure (and converts) the values to data types that can be converted to JSON, for example, datetime to str .",
      "section_inline_code": [
        "PATCH",
        "PUT",
        ".model_dump()",
        "datetime",
        "str"
      ],
      "section_links": [],
      "code_refs": [
        {
          "type": "code_ref",
          "path": "../../docs_src/body_updates/tutorial002_py310.py",
          "highlight_lines": [
            28,
            29,
            30,
            31,
            32,
            33,
            34,
            35
          ],
          "raw": "{* ../../docs_src/body_updates/tutorial002_py310.py hl[28:35] *}",
          "section_id": "tutorial/body-updates::section-0007",
          "section_url": "https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/body-updates/#partial-updates-recap"
        }
      ],
      "code_blocks": []
    }
